# Git and code style

## Commits

- Use [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/): `feat:`, `fix:`, `test:`, `docs:`, `chore:`, `refactor:`, etc., with an imperative subject line (`add` not `added`).
- One logical change per commit when practical; do not mix unrelated fixes.
- Body optional; use it for non-obvious rationale, breaking changes, or migration notes—not narration.
- Do not add `Co-authored-by` or similar trailers for assistants/tools unless the project explicitly requires it.

## Pushes

- Push when CI-relevant work is complete and tests pass locally (`pytest`, `npm run build:web` as in CI).
- Prefer a clean `master`/`main` history over frequent broken pushes.

## Code and comments

- No comments that reference Cursor, Copilot, “AI”, or any assistant as the author; no “generated by” or chat-style explanations in source.
- Comments only where they prevent real confusion: invariants, non-obvious protocol/API constraints, or safety notes. Match tone and density of surrounding code.
- Do not add README, CONTRIBUTING, or changelog files unless the user asks.
